<subSubSection id="C35E6CAD4A4F8A0FADADF9A61D49FA13" lastPageId="42" lastPageNumber="43" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BFB3F264A4F8A0FADADF9A61D49FA13" blockId="41.[120,1225,1103,1727]" lastBlockId="42.[120,1225,225,588]" lastPageId="42" lastPageNumber="43" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
REMARKS: When J.G.R first examined the three cocoons, two of which had been pinned with the adults and cells from their nests, he was impressed by the fact that nest partitions were attached to the leaf-/petal-lined burrow wall. He interpreted this to mean that the nest-making female had first lined the burrow wall with the plant material and subsequently started making and provisioning the series of cells, one after another. C.J.P. suggested another explanation: might the female have appropriated the vacated nest of a 
<taxonomicName id="4C4444A54A4C8A0FAE11FF481DE8F8A3" box="[788,903,225,251]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B930E3344A4C8A0FAE11FF481DE8F8A3" box="[788,903,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Megachile</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the cell of which had been lined with leaves and petal snippets since no other megachilid is known to use both petal-leaflining and resin in nest construction? Although none of the preserved nest materials gave a hint of the cocoons or feces of an original owner of the cells, the preserved nest material is limited. It is hoped the discovery of the next nest of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4444A54A4C8A0FAE01FED11DF3F9C9" authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1988" box="[772,924,375,401]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Pseudoheriades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grandiceps">
<emphasis id="B930E3344A4C8A0FAE01FED11DF3F9C9" box="[772,924,375,401]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">P. grandiceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
will provide a definitive interpretation. Terry Griswold kindly pointed to us an account on the nest of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4444A54A4C8A0FA912FE351EA1F983" baseAuthorityName="Friese" baseAuthorityYear="1897" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Pseudoheriades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="moricei">
<emphasis id="B930E3344A4C8A0FA912FE351EA1F983" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Pseudoheriades moricei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD542D74A4C8A0FADFDFE681FA8F984" author="Krombein, K. V." box="[248,455,449,476]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" pagination="1 - 18" refId="ref22816" refString="Krombein, K. V. 1969. Life history notes on some Egyptian solitary wasps and bees and their associates (Hymenoptera: Aculeata). Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology 19: 1 - 18." type="journal article" year="1969">Krombein (1969)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C4444A54A4C8A0FACD7FE6B1C2DF983" baseAuthorityName="Friese" baseAuthorityYear="1897" box="[466,578,450,475]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Pseudoheriades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="moricei">
<emphasis id="B930E3344A4C8A0FACD7FE6B1C2DF983" box="[466,578,450,475]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">P. moricei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also uses trap nests and uses resin for the construction of both partitions and plug, the latter also including pebbles. No hint of the use of petals or leaves is given by Krombein, suggesting that the leaves and petals observed in nests of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4444A54A4C8A0FA96AFDA41ED2FA13" authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1988" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Pseudoheriades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grandiceps">
<emphasis id="B930E3344A4C8A0FA96AFDA41ED2FA13" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">P.grandiceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may have been previously placed by leafcutter bees.
</paragraph>
